          "comments": [
            {
              "originalPosition": 29,
              "body": "```suggestion\nThe CONNECT-IP method {{!CONNECT-IP=RFC9484}} allows an HTTP client to establish an IP tunnel through an HTTP proxy and exchange IP packets using either HTTP/3 Datagrams ({{Section 2.1 of !HTTP-DATAGRAMS=RFC9297}}) or DATAGRAM capsules ({{Section 3.5 of HTTP-DATAGRAMS}}). Similarly, CONNECT-ETHERNET {{!CONNECT-ETHERNET=I-D.ietf-masque-connect-ethernet}} allows sending Ethernet frames over HTTP Datagrams. These protocols send complete packets or frames by default, including all transport and network headers. This is a simple approach, but incurs per-packet overhead due to the repeated transmission of largely invariant header fields.\n```",
              "createdAt": "2026-02-24T03:58:21Z",
              "updatedAt": "2026-02-24T04:08:43Z"
            },
            {
              "originalPosition": 14,
              "body": "```suggestion\nThis document defines extensions for HTTP Datagram-based protocols that improve transmission efficiency by introducing templates for compressing or deriving datagram fields.\n```",
              "createdAt": "2026-02-24T04:01:16Z",
              "updatedAt": "2026-02-24T04:08:43Z"
            },
            {
              "originalPosition": 54,
              "body": "CID really makes me think of QUIC CIDs... probably better to just say Context ID?",
              "createdAt": "2026-02-24T04:05:13Z",
              "updatedAt": "2026-02-24T04:08:43Z"
            },
            {
              "originalPosition": 5,
              "body": "This title is getting to be a doozy!\n\nWould it be OK to call this compression?\n\n```suggestion\ntitle: \"Extensions to Compress and Derive Fields in HTTP Datagrams\"\nabbrev: \"HTTP Datagram Compression\"\n```",
              "createdAt": "2026-02-24T04:08:24Z",
              "updatedAt": "2026-02-24T04:08:43Z"
            }
          ]
        },
